# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __hash__, __eq__, __lt__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __hash__: false for all 10 — hashing protocol not in own __dict__.
# __eq__: false for all 10 — equality protocol not in own __dict__.
# __lt__: false for all 10 — ordering protocol not in own __dict__.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. The comparison protocol dunders (__hash__, __eq__, __lt__)
#   are not overridden in the Python-level __dict__ of any of the 10 types.
# asyncio.Future note: Future inherits hash and equality from object (identity-
#   based). It does not define __hash__ or __eq__ in its own __dict__ despite
#   having a meaningful state machine (PENDING/RUNNING/CANCELLED/FINISHED).
# asyncio.PriorityQueue note: PriorityQueue orders its stored items but defines
#   no __lt__ in its own __dict__ — the queue object itself is not ordered,
#   only the items it holds.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a boolean flag via set()/clear()/is_set()
#   methods; even though it has a logical boolean state, neither __eq__ nor
#   __lt__ is defined in asyncio.Event.__dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   behind acquire()/release() coroutines; no comparison protocol dunders are
#   defined in their __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

